<h2>Reviewing for O'Reilly</h2>
<p>As soon as I saw <em>Raphaël JS</em> I knew I wanted to read and review it as I came across the library a couple of years ago, back in my old job and even at that time the library was already well implemented with many features.</p>
<p>Although this was the case, I was immediately curious to see how an <strong>entire book</strong> could be written on what I remember to be a small graphics manipulation library and couldn't wait to have a proper play with it (now my JavaScript skillz have improved vastly since then, too!)</p>
<blockquote class="pullquote"><a href="http://raphaeljs.com/" target="_blank">Raphaël</a> is a small JavaScript library that should simplify your work with vector graphics on the web.</blockquote>
<h2>Demos</h2>
<p>Throughout the book there are many hands-on demos to complete and I've uploaded my attempts to <a href="http://labs.furzeface.com/RaphaelJS/" target="_blank">Furzeface Labs</a> so be sure to check out what I did there.</p>

<p>Chris launches into the book in his humorous and down to earth writing tone straight away in the preface, explaining what the book will be about and easing the reader into what's to be expected from Raphaël JS.</p>
<p>The first chapter, <strong>Why Raphaël is Great</strong> explains just that and gives the reader a chance immediately to start coding and creating a <a href="http://labs.furzeface.com/RaphaelJS/ChapterOne" target="_blank">proverbial "Hello, World!"</a> after about 10 lines!</p>
<p>The author then goes on to explain a little more in detail about what the library is, offering uses and even alternatives, but coming back to why Raphaël is the one for us, with enticing promises of what's to come.</p>
<p>The second chapter goes on to show in smaller steps how to implement the library into your website and reiterates the first chapter's activity, "<em>in case, like the author, you never read the introduction</em>" - an example of Chris's easygoing style, injecting fun into the book as every tech author should!</p>
<figure>
  <a href="http://labs.furzeface.com/RaphaelJS/ChapterOne" target="_blank"><img src="http://static.furzeface.com/img/blog/30/chapter_1.jpg" alt="Raphaël JS - chapter 1 demo"/></a>
  <figcaption>Chapter 1 - Hello, Raphaël!</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>After an extensive second chapter that definitely had already satisfied my curiosity as to how a book could be written on the subject, I felt like I was really getting to grips with the basics of drawing with Raphaël and after completing the demos I actually couldn't wait to race on and learn more.</p>
<p>Chris's style of writing again amused me and contributed to my keenness in wanting to read on.</p>
<p>I then learned about attaching events and creating sets of objects, the author going into detail that initially may seem quite verbose but all is always revealed with case studies and more hands-on demos, allowing the reader to get a real experience of using the library and a sense of achievement when a demo is coded up and actually works!</p>
<p>Don't worry - Chris doesn't go into <strong>too much</strong> detail:</p>
<blockquote class="pullquote">For more discussion of the deep philosophical underpinnings of Raphaël, you'll have to wait for the sequel to this book.</blockquote>
<h2>Let's get animated!</h2>
<p>After an introduction to paths, shapes and curves <a href="http://labs.furzeface.com/RaphaelJS/ChapterFour" target="_blank">(see my curves here)</a>, the reader is taught about animations and easing - I love Chris’s analogy for easing, relating it to our typical car journey in order to explain it to the novice reader.</p>
<p>The interactive demos in this section really got into the nitty gritty of what you can do with this library and I was thrilled to have built something with it that I was proud of, simply by following Chris's simple steps.</p>
