<p>I have to admit that I missed out a couple of the demos here, but only because I'm lazy. A full set of code to accompany the book is hosted here on <a href="http://jsfiddle.net/user/raphaeljs/fiddles/" target="_blank">JSFiddle</a>.</p>
<h2>Data Visualisation</h2>
<p>Now, this is what I'd really wanted to get into and had some ideas about what to use it for - data visualisation with Raphaël.</p>
<p>In the 6th Chapter we learn how to use <a href="http://readysetraphael.com/" target="_blank">Ready Set Raphaël</a> to import an SVG and turn in into a Raphaël malleable object in order to manipulate it with another JavaScript object of real world data.</p>
<p>After completing the <a href="http://labs.furzeface.com/RaphaelJS/ChapterSix" target="_blank">US states map demo</a>, dynamically populated with a dataset of unemployment rates, I went on to create my own SVG map of Europe using Ready Set Raphaël and this <a href="http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Blank_map_of_Europe.svg" target="_blank">Wikimedia Commons SVG map</a>, feeding it a dataset of places that I've visited.</p>
<p>I hope to extend this to make the map interactive in the near future, with users able to click on countries to get info and colour the places they want to go.</p>
