<h2>Further Adventures</h2>
<p>Now Chris tells of more advanced animations and shows in depth how to extend Raphaël - definitely going beyond what I would've first expected from this book (a welcome surprise of course) and I quote:</p>
<blockquote class="pullquote">RaphaëlJS takes a strong stance against that sort of unadventurous attitute.</blockquote>
<p>- I think he was talking about me...</p>
<p>The final chapter, titled <strong>Mobile, Global Variables, and Other Things That Hurt Less Than You Think</strong> delves a little deeper into said scary things and leaves the reader wanting to learn more and I for one will be doing my own research now.</p>
<p>I think Chris Wilson writes well in this book and gives a great introduction to Raphaël JS. He speaks to the reader in such a way that makes them feel at ease and teaches with great capability from the very first <em>hello-world-drawing-a-circle</em> activity to advanced methods of implementing this library.</p>
<p>I'd recommend this book as a good read for anyone wanting to learn about Raphaël or even just SVG manipulation or data visualisation in general as it gives good tips on how to logically draw up these images and display the given data, and provides a few laughs along the way.</p>

<h2>Finger Painting?</h2>
<p>I'll end with a quote from the man himself, Chris Wilson:</p>
<blockquote class="pullquote">Raphaël makes drawing on the page easy, but not so easy that you don’t still get a little paint on your fingers</blockquote>
<p>I definitely think this rings true and I'm going to finish my Raphaël experiments and hopefully use the library within a project at my workplace.</p>
<p>I've already got some great ideas for Raphaël!</p>
